2026-07-04 | Minimum Score of a Path Between Two Cities

	Question
Return the minimum possible score of a path between city 1 and city n.
	Key Insight
The important observation is that the path is allowed to revisit nodes and edges.
This means we are **not restricted to simple paths**.
Since city 1 and city n belong to the same connected component, we can:
•	Travel from city 1 to any city in the component.
•	Cross any road we want.
•	Come back if needed.
•	Eventually reach city n.
Therefore, the answer is simply:
		the minimum edge weight
		in the connected component
		containing city 1.
	Approach
1.	Build the adjacency list.
2.	Run DFS/BFS starting from city 1.
3.	Visit every node in its connected component.
4.	For every traversed edge:
			answer =
			min(answer, edgeWeight)
5.	Return the minimum edge weight found.
	Time Complexity
	O(n + m)
	where
		n = number of cities
		m = number of roads
	Space Complexity
	O(n + m)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int minScore(int n, vector<vector<int>>& roads) {
        vector<vector<pair<int,int>>> graph(n + 1);
        for(auto &e : roads) {
            graph[e[0]].push_back({e[1], e[2]});
            graph[e[1]].push_back({e[0], e[2]});
        }
        vector<bool> vis(n + 1, false);
        int ans = INT_MAX;
        queue<int> q;
        q.push(1);
        vis[1] = true;
        while(!q.empty()) {
            int u = q.front();
            q.pop();
            for(auto &[v, w] : graph[u]) {
                ans = min(ans, w);
                if(!vis[v]) {
                    vis[v] = true;
                    q.push(v);
                }
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
	Example
	Input:
		n = 4
		roads =
		[
		 [1,2,9],
		 [2,3,6],
		 [2,4,5],
		 [1,4,7]
		]
	Connected component containing city 1:
		{1,2,3,4}
	Minimum road distance in this component:
		5
	Output:
		5
	Key Insight
	Because roads and cities may be revisited any number of times, you can always detour to traverse any edge within the connected component containing city `1` and still reach city `n`. Hence, the minimum possible path score is simply the **smallest edge weight in that connected component**, which can be found with a single DFS or BFS in **O(n + m)** time.
